data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType`, which gives a clear failure message instead of an `InvalidCastException`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    Assert.AreEqual("email", ((EmailHandler)result).Type);
}
```

**Why this is better:**

- A wrong type produces a readable test failure (`Assert.IsInstanceOfType failed`) instead of an unhandled `InvalidCastException`.
- The generic overload `IsInstanceOfType<T>` (MSTest v3+) avoids passing `typeof(...)` manually.
- The cast on the last line is now safe since the assertion above already validated the type.
